00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:20.260 --> 00:00:21.560
&gt;&gt; Betsy Peterson: Hello, everyone.

00:00:21.560 --> 00:00:24.860
I'm Betsy Peterson, director of
the American Folklife Center here

00:00:24.860 --> 00:00:27.830
at the Library of Congress
and I want to welcome you

00:00:27.830 --> 00:00:32.900
to the latest presentation in the
Benjamin Botkin Lecture Series.

00:00:32.900 --> 00:00:37.410
The Botkin series is an opportunity
for the American Folklife Center

00:00:37.410 --> 00:00:44.820
to present the very best research
from leading scholars in folklore,

00:00:44.820 --> 00:00:48.970
ethnomusicology, world
history, and cultural heritage.

00:00:48.970 --> 00:00:52.680
It also allows us to
enhance our collections.

00:00:52.680 --> 00:00:57.390
And by that, what I mean is each
of these lectures are videotaped

00:00:57.390 --> 00:01:00.810
and they become a part
of our archive.

00:01:00.810 --> 00:01:05.500
They also are eventually
posted in the library's website

00:01:05.500 --> 00:01:09.200
and made available to Internet
patrons throughout the world

00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:11.700
and are preserved for
future generations.

00:01:11.700 --> 00:01:15.850
So with all of that
description, please let me ask

00:01:15.850 --> 00:01:18.690
if you have any electronic
devices turned

00:01:18.690 --> 00:01:21.750
on at this point, please
turn them off.

00:01:21.750 --> 00:01:23.760
We would greatly appreciate it.

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:26.050
And while you're doing that,

00:01:26.050 --> 00:01:29.870
let me tell you a little
bit about today's lecture.

00:01:29.870 --> 00:01:31.260
Today, I have the owner honor

00:01:31.260 --> 00:01:35.770
of introducing the distinguished
scholar Gearóid Ó hAllmhuráin.

00:01:35.770 --> 00:01:40.070
Professor Ó hAllmhuráin is
an award-winning Irish musician

00:01:40.070 --> 00:01:43.400
ethnomusicologist and
cultural historian.

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:48.550
He is formerly the Jefferson
Smurfit Professor of Irish studies

00:01:48.550 --> 00:01:53.500 position:56%
and Professor of Music at the
University of Missouri in St. Louis.

00:01:53.500 --> 00:01:56.990
And he currently holds the
bilingual Johnson chair

00:01:56.990 --> 00:02:03.900 position:56%
in Québec &amp; Canadian Irish studies
at Concordia University in Montréal.

00:02:03.900 --> 00:02:08.440
A native of County Clare, he has
performed, broadcast, adjudicated,

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:13.250 position:56%
and lectured on Irish music
throughout Europe and North America.

00:02:13.250 --> 00:02:16.690
He holds degrees from
University College Cork,

00:02:16.690 --> 00:02:20.870
Queens University Belfast
and the Sorbonne.

00:02:20.870 --> 00:02:22.970
His musical career is

00:02:22.970 --> 00:02:26.120
as distinguished as
his academic career.

00:02:26.120 --> 00:02:30.650
A formal member of the
Kilfenora Ceili Band,

00:02:30.650 --> 00:02:35.530 position:56%
he is a five-time all-Ireland
champion musician on uilleann pipes,

00:02:35.530 --> 00:02:37.950
concertina, and ceili band.

00:02:37.950 --> 00:02:42.010
And he is a fourth-generation
Clare concertina player.

00:02:42.010 --> 00:02:45.560
He's also produced numerous
CDs, documentary films,

00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:49.070
and radio programs, and
is a frequent commentator

00:02:49.070 --> 00:02:51.460
on Irish music and culture.

00:02:51.460 --> 00:02:56.680
He is also the author of a pocket
history of Irish traditional music,

00:02:56.680 --> 00:03:00.230
which has just been
re-released as a short history

00:03:00.230 --> 00:03:04.820
of Irish traditional music as
well as writing numerous chapters

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:07.970
and articles on Irish
music and culture.

00:03:07.970 --> 00:03:12.150
His widely acclaimed book,
Flowing Tides: History and Memory

00:03:12.150 --> 00:03:14.090
in an Irish Soundscape,

00:03:14.090 --> 00:03:18.930
was published by Oxford
University press in 2016.

00:03:18.930 --> 00:03:22.010
Both books are being
offered for sale today

00:03:22.010 --> 00:03:25.250
by the LOC bookshop
just right outside.

00:03:25.250 --> 00:03:27.730
And Professor Ó hAllmhuráin
will be taking part

00:03:27.730 --> 00:03:31.310
in a book signing immediately
following his talk.

00:03:31.310 --> 00:03:35.730
So again, thank you for coming
today, and please join me

00:03:35.730 --> 00:03:39.210
in welcoming Profewssor Ó
hAllmhuráin for his talk

00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:44.200
on Flowing Tides: Musical Memory,
History, and Global Culture

00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:45.730
in County Clare, Ireland.

00:03:45.730 --> 00:03:47.030
Thanks.

