00:07:06.810 --> 00:07:11.970
My presentation today, however,
takes us beyond the world of books

00:07:11.970 --> 00:07:16.020
and the world of text
into the world of sound.

00:07:16.020 --> 00:07:21.410
To another time and another place
on the western fringe of Europe,

00:07:21.410 --> 00:07:25.250
where culture and politics
have also clashed,

00:07:25.250 --> 00:07:29.810
leaving in their wake a
soundscape that has endured

00:07:29.810 --> 00:07:34.550
and thrived both locally
and globally.

00:07:34.550 --> 00:07:38.930
Ireland, as many of you
know, is a natural haven

00:07:38.930 --> 00:07:41.980
on the Atlantic seaways
that link Nordic Europe

00:07:41.980 --> 00:07:43.840
with the Mediterranean Sea.

00:07:43.840 --> 00:07:49.660
For 8,000 years, it has experienced
cultural and economic contact

00:07:49.660 --> 00:07:55.060
with people and civilizations
along this oceanic fringe from Cork

00:07:55.060 --> 00:07:58.670
to Compostela, from
Limerick to Narvik.

00:07:58.670 --> 00:08:03.530
These exchanges brought priests,
traders, migrants and settlers

00:08:03.530 --> 00:08:05.540
to Ireland over the centuries.

00:08:05.540 --> 00:08:09.500
From Mesolithic hunters who crossed
the land bridge from Scotland

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:12.690 position:56%
to Ireland to the Eastern European's

00:08:12.690 --> 00:08:16.610
who serviced the recent
Celtic Tiger economy,

00:08:16.610 --> 00:08:21.660
each wave of newcomers brought
artistic and material goods,

00:08:21.660 --> 00:08:27.250
languages, music and folkways
that mingled and merged

00:08:27.250 --> 00:08:32.060
to form Ireland's vibrant
mosaic of cultures.

00:08:32.060 --> 00:08:36.890
Guarding Ireland's main
river archery, the Shannon,

00:08:36.890 --> 00:08:41.170
Clare separates the barren
wilderness of the western province

00:08:41.170 --> 00:08:46.110
of Connacht from the rich farmlands
of Munster in the south of Ireland.

00:08:46.110 --> 00:08:52.480
Prolonged periods of geological
time conspired to surround Clare

00:08:52.480 --> 00:08:58.970
on three sides by water and
insulated from its neighbors.

00:08:58.970 --> 00:09:04.990
Its only land access is through
the mountains of Slieve Aughty

00:09:04.990 --> 00:09:08.980
or across the [inaudible] of
the Burren where according

00:09:08.980 --> 00:09:13.840
to one Cromwellian general, there
was not enough wood to hang a man,

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:17.510
enough water to drown a man,
or enough dirt to bury a man.

00:09:17.510 --> 00:09:20.100
[ Laughter ]

00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:23.690
This is what the Burren
looks like today,

00:09:23.690 --> 00:09:28.300
as it did when the
Cromwellian cynic visited.

00:09:28.300 --> 00:09:33.320
Indeed, human history in the
Burren predates the Cromwellians

00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:35.830
by 6,000 years.

00:09:35.830 --> 00:09:41.080
Its first Neolithic farmers
arrived about 4000 BC.

00:09:41.080 --> 00:09:47.150 position:56%
And since then, human traffic in and
out of Clare has continued unabated.

00:09:47.150 --> 00:09:53.960
Its 7,000 archaeological sites
contain Bronze Age tombs,

00:09:53.960 --> 00:10:00.520
Iron Age forts -- like this one
-- and early Christian churches.

00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:04.850
Clare also contains the
remains of Viking, Norman,

00:10:04.850 --> 00:10:06.150
and [inaudible] settlers.

00:10:06.150 --> 00:10:11.060
This is a well-known landmark in
County Clare that I'm sure many

00:10:11.060 --> 00:10:14.720
of you are familiar with,
Bunratty Castle, which was built

00:10:14.720 --> 00:10:18.300
by the Norman Richard the Clare.

00:10:18.300 --> 00:10:22.500
Landlord estates, garrison
towns, chapel villages

00:10:22.500 --> 00:10:28.100 position:56%
and railroads reshaped the geography
of Clare in more recent times,

00:10:28.100 --> 00:10:32.150
as did famine, eviction,
and immigration.

00:10:32.150 --> 00:10:38.380
From a land perspective, Clare is
a remote, liminal place in the west

00:10:38.380 --> 00:10:42.430
of Ireland to where the
Celts supposedly retreated

00:10:42.430 --> 00:10:45.020
in the centuries before
the birth of Christ

00:10:45.020 --> 00:10:48.370
after fighting a long
rearguard action

00:10:48.370 --> 00:10:50.950
from the Alps to the Atlantic.

00:10:50.950 --> 00:10:54.960
Creative writers and social
scientists have been intrigued

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:58.260
by this liminality.

00:10:58.260 --> 00:11:01.250
In literary and socio-analytical
text,

00:11:01.250 --> 00:11:05.340
Clare and its hinterlands are
designated sanctuaries of tradition

00:11:05.340 --> 00:11:10.340
and authenticity, not to
mention back orders of madness,

00:11:10.340 --> 00:11:13.930
repression, and social enemy.

00:11:13.930 --> 00:11:16.310
A maritime compass, however,

00:11:16.310 --> 00:11:20.350
presents a very different
perspective of this region.

00:11:20.350 --> 00:11:24.950 position:56%
Situated at the mouth of the
Shannon, Clare was in the slipstream

00:11:24.950 --> 00:11:30.380
of ocean trade and migration
since early Christian times.

00:11:30.380 --> 00:11:34.030
The cults of its early
Christian saints, for example,

00:11:34.030 --> 00:11:38.930
can be found in Scotland,
Wales, Cornwall, and Brittany.

00:11:38.930 --> 00:11:43.810
In the wake of the voyages of
discovery, Ireland, which was once

00:11:43.810 --> 00:11:48.340
on the edge of the known world
now found itself near the center

00:11:48.340 --> 00:11:50.210
of the New World.

00:11:50.210 --> 00:11:54.440
During this extended age of
sale, coastal communities

00:11:54.440 --> 00:12:00.060
on Clare's Erris Peninsula provided
river pilots for toll ships going

00:12:00.060 --> 00:12:04.050
up the river Shannon to Limerick,
which was a last port of call

00:12:04.050 --> 00:12:06.840
for fleets crossing
the North Atlantic.

00:12:06.840 --> 00:12:10.870
Before the arrival of railroads
in the mid-19th century,

00:12:10.870 --> 00:12:15.420
a network of satellite ports
dotted Clare's fractal coast

00:12:15.420 --> 00:12:19.510
from Lough Derg on the Shannon to
Lukead [phonetic] on the Atlantic

00:12:19.510 --> 00:12:22.950
and North towards Galway Bay.

00:12:22.950 --> 00:12:29.030
Like this Port of Kilrush, which is
on the mouth of the river Shannon,

00:12:29.030 --> 00:12:33.730
they all shared some sense
of clans' local engagement

00:12:33.730 --> 00:12:35.730
with the outside world.

00:12:35.730 --> 00:12:38.350
[Inaudible] culture
currents reached Clare

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:45.510
from rather unlikely destinations
in the past two millennia.

00:12:45.510 --> 00:12:49.790
Coptic stonework, for example,
similar to carvings found

00:12:49.790 --> 00:12:51.930
in the lower reaches
of the river Nile,

00:12:51.930 --> 00:12:55.270
survives in early Christian
churches in the Burren

00:12:55.270 --> 00:12:58.560
in the Aran islands,
it's geological annex.

00:12:58.560 --> 00:13:01.900
Here, for example, you
see one of these crosses

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:03.950
in the village of Kilfenora.

00:13:03.950 --> 00:13:05.930
And I'd like to direct
your attention

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:09.890
to the second panel
beneath the bishop.

00:13:09.890 --> 00:13:14.830
And if you look at the figure on
the right-hand side of the screen,

00:13:14.830 --> 00:13:19.120
you will notice the flat,
Coptic Egyptian cross.

00:13:19.120 --> 00:13:24.310
This is a rare example of
stone masonry that traveled

00:13:24.310 --> 00:13:27.960
from the lower reaches of the
Nile across the Mediterranean,

00:13:27.960 --> 00:13:35.850
out through the point of Gibraltar
and around Spain, traveling north

00:13:35.850 --> 00:13:38.170
into the western part of Ireland

00:13:38.170 --> 00:13:42.830
where these stonemasons
created Coptic artifacts.

00:13:47.290 --> 00:13:50.670
During the 12th and 13th centuries,

00:13:50.670 --> 00:13:56.210
avant-garde European scholasticism
found eager patrons in Clare

00:13:56.210 --> 00:14:03.180 position:56%
when the old Gaelic world synergized
by a new European age of faith.

00:14:03.180 --> 00:14:07.800
Here, for example, is the
Franciscan Friary in Ennis

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:14.490 position:56%
in County Clare dating from the
mid-13th century, and again evidence

00:14:14.490 --> 00:14:18.980
of European migration
to the west of Ireland.

00:14:18.980 --> 00:14:23.930
The arrival of mendicant orders,
particularly the Augustinians,

00:14:23.930 --> 00:14:29.750
the Franciscans, the Dominicans,
changed Irish Christianity

00:14:29.750 --> 00:14:33.520
and linking it with
a new renaissance

00:14:33.520 --> 00:14:36.270
of European Christianity.

00:14:36.270 --> 00:14:40.050
Outward-bound currents,
too, were impressive.

00:14:40.050 --> 00:14:44.020
Clare [inaudible] families sent
their offspring to University

00:14:44.020 --> 00:14:48.860
in Prague, Leuven, and
Paris during the Penal Era

00:14:48.860 --> 00:14:52.690
when its military exiles
fought imperial wars

00:14:52.690 --> 00:14:58.010
and explored New World colonies
from new Newfoundland to Brazil.

00:14:58.010 --> 00:15:04.020
Nowhere is the imprint of global
culture flows more pronounced,

00:15:04.020 --> 00:15:07.930
however, then in Clare's
traditional soundscape.

00:15:07.930 --> 00:15:11.060
That has been a site
of cultural convergence

00:15:11.060 --> 00:15:14.330
and coalescence for centuries.

00:15:14.330 --> 00:15:17.530
Music, irrespective of genre,

00:15:17.530 --> 00:15:22.200
is a nomadic art whose
journeys are frequently lost

00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:26.260
in what French historian
Jacques Le Goff called the

00:15:26.260 --> 00:15:30.550
"indefinable residue of
historical analyses."

00:15:30.550 --> 00:15:36.870
The transcultural odyssey of the
Arabic guitar, the African banjo,

00:15:36.870 --> 00:15:42.100
and European Baroque dancing all
bear witness to this phenomenon.

00:15:42.100 --> 00:15:45.960
In contrast to the architects
of the Celtic twilight

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:49.970
in the late 19th century who saw
the west of Ireland as a place

00:15:49.970 --> 00:15:56.500
of timeless, romantic authenticity,
Clare musicians have a long history

00:15:56.500 --> 00:16:00.390
of moving beyond the
injunctions of the past.

00:16:00.390 --> 00:16:03.930
By the end of the 18th
century, the Italian violin --

00:16:03.930 --> 00:16:07.410
which we see here in
the case beside us --

00:16:07.410 --> 00:16:11.690
had reached Clare and was
notarized and nativized

00:16:11.690 --> 00:16:14.320
as the Irish fiddle,
[speaking Gaelic].

00:16:14.320 --> 00:16:19.960
Baroque flutes and fifes
were also nativized.

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:22.610
In the half-century
after the great famine,

00:16:22.610 --> 00:16:25.670
the region welcomed
German concertinas --

00:16:25.670 --> 00:16:29.350
which you'll hear at the
end of this performance --

00:16:29.350 --> 00:16:35.560 position:56%
Sicilian coral societies and British
and German style brass bands,

00:16:35.560 --> 00:16:39.580
American Victrolas in
jazz, Italian accordions,

00:16:39.580 --> 00:16:43.500
and Balkan bouzoukis all
arrived during the next century,

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:48.720
ferried in by trains,
planes, and automobiles.

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:55.530
Clare's bricolage of Irish tunes
today contains Scottish reels,

00:16:55.530 --> 00:17:00.990
French galops, Bavarian marches,
and North Hungarian horn pipes,

00:17:00.990 --> 00:17:05.170
while its set dancers
trace their ancestry

00:17:05.170 --> 00:17:09.860
to the choreographers
of [inaudible] France.

00:17:09.860 --> 00:17:15.110
Despite their so-called geographic
isolation on the outer edge

00:17:15.110 --> 00:17:19.640
of Europe, Clare music makers
have released an impressive corpus

00:17:19.640 --> 00:17:25.940
of tunes and songs into the
transcultural tide of world music.

00:17:25.940 --> 00:17:30.150
I've no doubt that many of you
are familiar with these figures.

00:17:30.150 --> 00:17:34.370
Master performers like Martin
Hayes, Michael Tubridy,

00:17:34.370 --> 00:17:39.010
and Sharon Shannon are not just
local carriers of tradition.

00:17:39.010 --> 00:17:43.320
These are the global
faces of Clare today.

00:17:43.320 --> 00:17:50.790 position:56%
Similarly, the Kilfenora Ceili Band,
the oldest dance band in Ireland,

00:17:50.790 --> 00:17:54.530
performs Clare's repertoire
in symphony halls

00:17:54.530 --> 00:17:57.850 position:56%
and folk festivals across the globe.

