00:18:02.460 --> 00:18:06.020
for the music, is a
ubiquitous calling card

00:18:06.020 --> 00:18:10.370
that beckons tourists west
from Dublin to the festivals

00:18:10.370 --> 00:18:13.160
and singing pubs of Clare.

00:18:13.160 --> 00:18:18.220
Every summer, its towns and
villages become makeshift academies

00:18:18.220 --> 00:18:23.000
of tradition, none more so than
Milltown Malbay and Doolin,

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:27.820
Ireland's mecca of traditional
music, known to music pilgrims

00:18:27.820 --> 00:18:32.330
and aficionados from Jura to
Japan, from the Austrian Alps

00:18:32.330 --> 00:18:35.370
to the Pampas of Argentina.

00:18:35.370 --> 00:18:39.960
Today, traditional music
in Clare no longer lives

00:18:39.960 --> 00:18:45.620
in little thatched cottages in
isolated places, nor does it travel

00:18:45.620 --> 00:18:49.720
by donkey and cart along
lonesome country roads.

00:18:49.720 --> 00:18:55.190
It is, in fact, a polyverse of
music communities whose voices are

00:18:55.190 --> 00:19:01.370
as vibrant in the music pubs of New
York, Washington, D.C., Montréal,

00:19:01.370 --> 00:19:04.900
Chicago, and San Francisco
as they are

00:19:04.900 --> 00:19:08.530
in the dance halls of
Kilfenora and Tulla.

00:19:08.530 --> 00:19:12.980
Focusing on the interplay
between history and memory,

00:19:12.980 --> 00:19:17.240
which are not synonymous, by the
way, my book Flowing Tides --

00:19:17.240 --> 00:19:22.970 position:56%
which is available today -- examines
the impact of global cultural flows

00:19:22.970 --> 00:19:28.480
on Clare's so-called isolated
soundscape from the Napoleonic wars

00:19:28.480 --> 00:19:35.810
to the Celtic Tiger boom in the
period from 1995 until 2005.

00:19:35.810 --> 00:19:43.390
It focuses ostensibly on musical
roots but also musical routes,

00:19:43.390 --> 00:19:45.620
both in Clare and beyond,

00:19:45.620 --> 00:19:49.890
to a century of austere
British colonialism

00:19:49.890 --> 00:19:54.010
and an equally strained
century of post-colonialism,

00:19:54.010 --> 00:19:59.380
both of which exposed the region
to intense musical traffic.

00:19:59.380 --> 00:20:02.940
Allow me to take you
through very briefly some

00:20:02.940 --> 00:20:08.460 position:56%
of the key musical moments and what
they tell us about the local as well

00:20:08.460 --> 00:20:11.970
as the global music
history of the region.

00:20:11.970 --> 00:20:17.210
Several key political and
economic events sourced

00:20:17.210 --> 00:20:19.750
in Clare during the 19th century

00:20:19.750 --> 00:20:23.760
and that were felt
throughout the British Empire

00:20:23.760 --> 00:20:28.310 position:56%
and among Irish diasporic
communities throughout the world are

00:20:28.310 --> 00:20:32.900
centered and located and
articulated initially

00:20:32.900 --> 00:20:37.600
in Clare before spreading outwards
throughout the island of Ireland

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:41.820
and elsewhere throughout
the British Empire.

00:20:41.820 --> 00:20:47.470
For example, the election of
Catholic lawyer Daniel O'Connell

00:20:47.470 --> 00:20:52.200
to the British Parliament for
Clare in 1828 and the passing

00:20:52.200 --> 00:20:58.220
of Catholic emancipation a year
later changed the lives of millions

00:20:58.220 --> 00:21:04.790
of Catholics not just in Ireland
but throughout the British Empire.

00:21:04.790 --> 00:21:08.060
Although the Penal Laws,
which delight denied civil

00:21:08.060 --> 00:21:12.390
and religious rights to Catholics,
were now officially revoked,

00:21:12.390 --> 00:21:17.040
the long-term impact of
rapid population growth

00:21:17.040 --> 00:21:20.000 position:56%
and unsustainable economic practices

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:26.270
in Ireland proved ultimately
far more catastrophic.

00:21:26.270 --> 00:21:28.940
This was evident in Clare

00:21:28.940 --> 00:21:32.750
in the decades following
the Napoleonic wars.

00:21:32.750 --> 00:21:37.170
But its population
peaked as never before.

00:21:37.170 --> 00:21:39.240
Remember today the population

00:21:39.240 --> 00:21:43.510
of Ireland is approximately
4 million people.

00:21:43.510 --> 00:21:50.660
In 1821, the population of
County Clare was 208,000.

00:21:50.660 --> 00:21:56.020
But it grew to 286,000 on the eve

00:21:56.020 --> 00:22:00.590
of the Great Famine,
which began in 1845.

00:22:00.590 --> 00:22:05.400
Clare, however, was
decimated by this catastrophe.

00:22:05.400 --> 00:22:10.720
And I want to show you some images
that speak to that catastrophe.

00:22:10.720 --> 00:22:14.660
Unlike other famines and
particularly modern famines,

00:22:14.660 --> 00:22:16.600
the Great Irish Famine
-- which is was one

00:22:16.600 --> 00:22:22.580
of many famines throughout the
17th and 18th century and indeed

00:22:22.580 --> 00:22:25.830
into the latter years
of the 19th century --

00:22:25.830 --> 00:22:29.600
the Great Famine was
not a pictorial famine.

00:22:29.600 --> 00:22:33.010
There were no photojournalists
like Steve Winick [phonetic] --

00:22:33.010 --> 00:22:34.620
[ Laughter ]

00:22:34.620 --> 00:22:38.040
-- or any other major
photographic figure.

00:22:38.040 --> 00:22:43.670
The people who chronicled
the Great Irish Famine were

00:22:43.670 --> 00:22:46.080
government statisticians.

00:22:46.080 --> 00:22:52.030
Eventually, the London Illustrated
News sent illustrators to Ireland

00:22:52.030 --> 00:22:57.680
to document the famine, and here
we have an example of their work.

00:22:57.680 --> 00:23:05.490
This is a deserted village in the
Erris Peninsula in Southwest Clare,

00:23:05.490 --> 00:23:13.870
which was not simply deserted
by famine but was evicted

00:23:13.870 --> 00:23:19.900
by the local landlord for --
excuse me -- nonpayment of rent.

00:23:19.900 --> 00:23:23.230
What's interesting is that if
you travel throughout the west

00:23:23.230 --> 00:23:26.280
of Ireland you'll see many examples

00:23:26.280 --> 00:23:32.810
of village communities completely
abandoned leaving nothing

00:23:32.810 --> 00:23:37.440
in their wake except the
foundations of their houses.

00:23:37.440 --> 00:23:41.960
Here is another example perhaps
if I can use the expression,

00:23:41.960 --> 00:23:47.030
the poster child of the Great
Irish Famine, Brigit O'Donnell

00:23:47.030 --> 00:23:54.450
and her children photographed
or drawn so to speak in 1849

00:23:54.450 --> 00:23:59.430
by the illustrator from the
London Illustrated News.

00:23:59.430 --> 00:24:05.400
The area of Clare and particularly
Southwest Clare topped the national

00:24:05.400 --> 00:24:08.350 position:56%
grid in famine deaths and evictions.

00:24:08.350 --> 00:24:14.210
By 1851, its population
had fallen to 212,000.

00:24:14.210 --> 00:24:20.710
A century later, less than
100,000 people lived in Clare.

00:24:20.710 --> 00:24:26.270
By now, its voluntary exiles were
dispersed throughout the New World

00:24:26.270 --> 00:24:31.130
in Canada, the United
States, Argentina, Australia,

00:24:31.130 --> 00:24:33.540
New Zealand, and South Africa.

00:24:33.540 --> 00:24:40.210
An estimated 400,000 people left
Clare in the past two centuries.

00:24:40.210 --> 00:24:46.310
People of Clare extraction today
who live overseas outnumber those

00:24:46.310 --> 00:24:52.610
who live in Clare by a
ratio of three to one.

00:24:52.610 --> 00:24:56.350
All of these events,
from the excitement

00:24:56.350 --> 00:25:00.030
of Napoleon Bonaparte's
battles and campaigns

00:25:00.030 --> 00:25:05.520
to Daniel O'Connell's electoral
victories, to the human tragedy

00:25:05.520 --> 00:25:11.380
of famine and diastral all
found a voice and a sonic memory

00:25:11.380 --> 00:25:15.500
in the music, song, and
dance of County Clare.

00:25:15.500 --> 00:25:18.900
The long campaign to remove Ireland

00:25:18.900 --> 00:25:21.710
from the British Empire
had a critical impact

00:25:21.710 --> 00:25:24.050
on the lives of Clare people.

00:25:24.050 --> 00:25:27.820
From the Fenian movement -- which
you are very familiar with here

00:25:27.820 --> 00:25:32.490
in the United States -- and the
land war to the plan of campaign

00:25:32.490 --> 00:25:35.190
and the War of Independence.

00:25:35.190 --> 00:25:38.210
But this particular
photograph is interesting.

00:25:38.210 --> 00:25:41.780
Is a photograph from the
land war in County Clare.

00:25:41.780 --> 00:25:48.570 position:56%
And remember within a 30-year
window, now we have photojournalism.

00:25:48.570 --> 00:25:54.080
Now we're familiar with
the sight and sounds

00:25:54.080 --> 00:25:59.780
of cameras chronicling political
events, unlike the experience

00:25:59.780 --> 00:26:04.000
of the Great Famine which
was not a photographic event.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:09.050
And again, we're still
singing songs and ballads

00:26:09.050 --> 00:26:12.930
about the land war in County Clare.

00:26:12.930 --> 00:26:16.620
Ninety years after
electing Daniel O'Connell,

00:26:16.620 --> 00:26:21.610
Clare elected the American-born
Eamon de Valera to Parliament

00:26:21.610 --> 00:26:26.390
on a Sinn Fein ticket in 1917.

00:26:26.390 --> 00:26:32.540
Born in New York City of an Irish
mother and a Spanish father,

00:26:32.540 --> 00:26:37.480
Eamon de Valera was a daunting
and enigmatic political figure.

00:26:37.480 --> 00:26:42.810
He dominated Irish life for most
of the 20th century as a national

00:26:42.810 --> 00:26:45.530
and international statesman
and an architect

00:26:45.530 --> 00:26:48.570
of social and cultural change.

00:26:48.570 --> 00:26:52.890
All of these symbolic events and
characters are remembered as much

00:26:52.890 --> 00:26:57.280
in music and song as
they are textual history.

00:26:57.280 --> 00:27:03.720 position:56%
Feigning separatism, and
19th-century politics are still sung

00:27:03.720 --> 00:27:10.580
about today in Clare and among
Clare exilic communities.

00:27:10.580 --> 00:27:14.300
Likewise, the first and
second temperance movements,

00:27:14.300 --> 00:27:19.350
public processions led by
marching bands were popular rituals

00:27:19.350 --> 00:27:22.540
of this anti-drink crusade.

00:27:22.540 --> 00:27:28.670
Fife and drum bands formed to rally
the faithful and to route the evil

00:27:28.670 --> 00:27:31.450 position:56%
of drink in rural and urban Ireland.

00:27:31.450 --> 00:27:33.750
Imagine that.

00:27:36.060 --> 00:27:40.350
These drum bands were
formed initially

00:27:40.350 --> 00:27:43.470
to perform at religious events.

00:27:43.470 --> 00:27:48.840
But eventually they began to
arouse less devout congregations

00:27:48.840 --> 00:27:53.280
of Irish hurling matches
and football matches,

00:27:53.280 --> 00:27:58.200
at land league rallies and trade
union meetings, eventually morphing

00:27:58.200 --> 00:28:00.560
into brass and reed bands.

00:28:00.560 --> 00:28:06.730
As funds improved, these ensembles
also spread musical literacy.

00:28:06.730 --> 00:28:12.810 position:56%
Like this particular brass and reed
band from Kilfenora in County Clare.

00:28:12.810 --> 00:28:18.830 position:56%
And this band was a very active
musical ensemble until the Irish War

00:28:18.830 --> 00:28:23.500
of Independence when the blackened
towns, destroyed their instruments,

00:28:23.500 --> 00:28:28.040
in an act of social
and cultural reprisal.

00:28:28.040 --> 00:28:31.350
Some were trained by
British Army band masters

00:28:31.350 --> 00:28:35.390
who had sufficient peace time on
their hands between the Crimean

00:28:35.390 --> 00:28:39.820
and the Second Boer War to make
a real artistic contribution

00:28:39.820 --> 00:28:42.590
to her majesty's subjects.

00:28:42.590 --> 00:28:46.440
New instruments were also
introduced during this period,

00:28:46.440 --> 00:28:50.710
in particular the Anglo-German
concertino --

00:28:50.710 --> 00:28:54.800
which you'll hear in
a few moments --

00:28:54.800 --> 00:28:58.260
which became a sonic
insignia in Clare

00:28:58.260 --> 00:29:02.310
that brought musical
liberation, particularly to women

00:29:02.310 --> 00:29:05.440
in a male-dominated world.

00:29:05.440 --> 00:29:09.180
Cultural nationalism
designed, brokered,

00:29:09.180 --> 00:29:14.450
and delivered by the Gaelic league
was a potent mobilizing agent

00:29:14.450 --> 00:29:18.860
in late 19th century Ireland,
especially its rhetoric

00:29:18.860 --> 00:29:22.470
of linguistic pride,
grassroots activism,

00:29:22.470 --> 00:29:26.610
and competitive music making
that spread systemically

00:29:26.610 --> 00:29:30.230
from metropolitan areas like
Dublin, Cork and Limerick

00:29:30.230 --> 00:29:34.630
out into the rural
peripheries of Ireland.

00:29:34.630 --> 00:29:39.750
This ideoscape reached its apogee
in Clare and in other parts

00:29:39.750 --> 00:29:44.370
of the country with the
Rebellion of 1916 and the War

00:29:44.370 --> 00:29:48.510
of Independence that
followed in 1919.

00:29:48.510 --> 00:29:54.490
Caught in a vortex of chaos
and terror, musicians, too,

00:29:54.490 --> 00:29:57.480
fell victim to the
atrocities of war.

00:29:57.480 --> 00:30:00.620
Especially the Black
and Tans which were

00:30:00.620 --> 00:30:03.550
who were irregular British
troops sent to Ireland

00:30:03.550 --> 00:30:08.200
to reinforce the Royal
Irish Constabulary police.

00:30:08.200 --> 00:30:13.550
During these turbulent times,
house dances were rated,

00:30:13.550 --> 00:30:17.200
instruments were destroyed --
as in the case of this band --

00:30:17.200 --> 00:30:19.920
and musicians were
forced to immigrate

00:30:19.920 --> 00:30:22.570
to escape political violence.

00:30:22.570 --> 00:30:26.300
In the wake of the Anglo-Irish
Treaty and Civil War,

00:30:26.300 --> 00:30:31.340
the fledgling Irish Free
State proved rather powerless

00:30:31.340 --> 00:30:37.630
to hold back the rising tide of
the roaring '20s from America.

00:30:37.630 --> 00:30:42.020
That flowed without end,
it seemed, into Ireland,

00:30:42.020 --> 00:30:46.510
particularly in the form of
jazz and its attendant sins.

00:30:46.510 --> 00:30:49.350
[ Laughter ]

00:30:49.350 --> 00:30:56.200
Here is an example of an Irish
jazz band, which came to prominence

00:30:56.200 --> 00:31:02.290
in the 1920s and '30s, taking
their cues from similar kinds

00:31:02.290 --> 00:31:08.300
of jazz bands that were active
throughout the United States.

00:31:08.300 --> 00:31:16.340 position:56%
Ireland's moral response to jazz was
to pass a draconian Dance Halls Act

00:31:16.340 --> 00:31:22.750
in 1935 which radically altered
the musical life of the nation.

00:31:22.750 --> 00:31:26.210
By the time World War
II began in 1939

00:31:26.210 --> 00:31:30.280
and the Irish Free State
declared itself neutral,

00:31:30.280 --> 00:31:36.290
Ireland's audiences had already
developed a taste for Hollywood

00:31:36.290 --> 00:31:41.460
and indeed modern as
well as ceili dancing.

00:31:41.460 --> 00:31:48.280
Now you will notice that in both of
these prints, this is a ceili band

00:31:48.280 --> 00:31:53.050
from County Clare an early
example of a ceili ensemble.

00:31:53.050 --> 00:31:56.990
But you'll notice that the
fiddle player just to the right

00:31:56.990 --> 00:32:00.740
of the piano is, in
fact, the banjo player

00:32:00.740 --> 00:32:03.290
at the center of the jazz band.

00:32:03.290 --> 00:32:09.170
So they're going back and
forth between two traditions.

00:32:09.170 --> 00:32:12.000
The countryside in
Clare and in other areas

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:16.200
of Ireland was now dotted with
small cinemas and dance halls.

00:32:16.200 --> 00:32:19.980
Most of them managed by the
priest, the Catholic priest,

00:32:19.980 --> 00:32:23.790
who brokered moral
agendas, vetted movies,

00:32:23.790 --> 00:32:27.710
formed ceili bands,
and paid the musicians.

00:32:27.710 --> 00:32:31.440
If the Emergency -- which
was the official title

00:32:31.440 --> 00:32:34.240
for the World War II
period in Ireland.

00:32:34.240 --> 00:32:38.370
Ireland, because it was neutral,
never referred to it publicly

00:32:38.370 --> 00:32:43.210
at least in the press the war.

00:32:43.210 --> 00:32:47.280
It was always referred to by
the rather euphemistic term

00:32:47.280 --> 00:32:52.080
in our Irish parlance
as The Emergency,

00:32:52.080 --> 00:32:58.470
which lasted between 1939 and 1945.

00:32:58.470 --> 00:33:01.220
So the Emergency, which
was the official term,

00:33:01.220 --> 00:33:04.290
seamed the country off
from the outside world.

00:33:04.290 --> 00:33:08.700
And indeed, the depression
that followed failed

00:33:08.700 --> 00:33:13.330
to stem the tide of freeing exiles.

00:33:13.330 --> 00:33:18.980
This flight of people sparked a
crisis that entered the psyche

00:33:18.980 --> 00:33:22.650
of the nation as the hungry '40s.

00:33:22.650 --> 00:33:26.990
Now I'd like to show
you a photograph taken

00:33:26.990 --> 00:33:31.580
by the famous American
photographer Dorothea Lange,

00:33:31.580 --> 00:33:33.890
who most of you Americans will know

00:33:33.890 --> 00:33:38.490
for her work chronicling the Great
Depression and the internment

00:33:38.490 --> 00:33:41.090
of Japanese communities, etc.,

00:33:41.090 --> 00:33:46.440
etc. And these two ladies were
photographed in County Clare

00:33:46.440 --> 00:33:51.380
in the fall of 1954,
and they're just

00:33:51.380 --> 00:33:54.060
about to leave Ireland for America.

00:33:54.060 --> 00:33:59.010
The immigration of young women,
particularly from rural areas,

00:33:59.010 --> 00:34:02.040
is very significant
because for the most part,

00:34:02.040 --> 00:34:05.140
women did not inherit land.

00:34:05.140 --> 00:34:11.230
And so they became the
diasporic members of the family,

00:34:11.230 --> 00:34:15.540
as in the case of these two women
the O'Hallaren [phonetic] sisters

00:34:15.540 --> 00:34:18.540
from Mount Callan in County Clare.

00:34:18.540 --> 00:34:23.640
These dull, sepia-toned
years saw hundreds

00:34:23.640 --> 00:34:30.200 position:56%
of Clare musicians fall victim to
anti-jazz crusades, priestly purges,

00:34:30.200 --> 00:34:35.070
and indeed forced exile to
quote/unquote heathen England --

00:34:35.070 --> 00:34:37.130
[ Laughter ]

00:34:37.130 --> 00:34:38.780
-- and America.

00:34:38.780 --> 00:34:44.110
If Clare was on the periphery
of Irish economic life

00:34:44.110 --> 00:34:48.480
in the early decades of Irish
independence, that isolation came

00:34:48.480 --> 00:34:56.250
to an end on the 24th of October
1945 when Captain Charles Blair --

00:34:56.250 --> 00:35:00.660
who most of you will know is the
husband of actress Marine O'Hara --

00:35:00.660 --> 00:35:03.200
piles at the first
commercial flight from New York

00:35:03.200 --> 00:35:07.240
to Shannon in a four engine DC-4.

00:35:07.240 --> 00:35:11.270
For the next four decades,
Shannon County Clare,

00:35:11.270 --> 00:35:14.080
the most westerly international
Airport in Europe --

00:35:14.080 --> 00:35:17.200
although I suppose the
Portuguese would dispute that --

00:35:17.200 --> 00:35:21.980
was a gateway for traffic
crossing the Atlantic.

00:35:21.980 --> 00:35:27.050
It also became the world's
first duty-free zone and a hub

00:35:27.050 --> 00:35:29.950
of international industrial
development,

00:35:29.950 --> 00:35:34.970
all of which changed perceived
notions of centers of peripheries

00:35:34.970 --> 00:35:38.900
in Clare and its west
of Ireland hinterland.

00:35:38.900 --> 00:35:42.640
From now on, America had
moved closer to the social

00:35:42.640 --> 00:35:44.910
and cultural life of the region.

00:35:44.910 --> 00:35:49.090
As American aircrews were ferried
back and forth to local hotels

00:35:49.090 --> 00:35:54.550
to rest between flights and
indeed relatives took vacations

00:35:54.550 --> 00:35:55.850
to the Old Country.

00:35:55.850 --> 00:36:01.810
In the 1960s, Shannon was
Clare's horn of plenty,

00:36:01.810 --> 00:36:04.590
a site of paid factory work,

00:36:04.590 --> 00:36:08.420
a place where material progress
was possible close to home

00:36:08.420 --> 00:36:11.010
without the burden of immigration.

00:36:11.010 --> 00:36:14.520
And indeed, if industrialization
lifted the region

00:36:14.520 --> 00:36:16.730
out of agrarian dependency,

00:36:16.730 --> 00:36:20.990
it did not make it
impervious to economic change.

00:36:20.990 --> 00:36:25.110
In the past half-century,
Shannon has experienced good

00:36:25.110 --> 00:36:30.110
and bad economic times, the latter
which brought prolonged periods

00:36:30.110 --> 00:36:32.930
of unemployment and immigration.

00:36:32.930 --> 00:36:37.400
Ennis, Clare's County town,
followed a similar although less

00:36:37.400 --> 00:36:39.540
intensive trajectory.

00:36:39.540 --> 00:36:44.560
Traditionally a farmers' town that
hosted historic fairs and markets,

00:36:44.560 --> 00:36:48.640
Ennis acquired light industry
after Irish independence.

00:36:48.640 --> 00:36:53.270 position:56%
And attempting to follow Shannon's
lead it expanded its industrial base

00:36:53.270 --> 00:36:54.760
in the 1960s.

00:36:54.760 --> 00:37:00.430
However, it really became an
international town in the 1990s

00:37:00.430 --> 00:37:05.700
when it became Ireland's
first Information Age town,

00:37:05.700 --> 00:37:10.110
a town in which every home
was connected to the Internet

00:37:10.110 --> 00:37:14.310
and every child became
computer literate.

00:37:14.310 --> 00:37:22.710
Clare's cultural life also
responded to these postwar changes.

00:37:22.710 --> 00:37:26.180
Brokered by Northern
piper Sean Reid --

00:37:26.180 --> 00:37:30.620
who you see here in the back
row second from the right --

00:37:30.620 --> 00:37:32.950
Reid and his cohorts
at [speaking Irish]

00:37:32.950 --> 00:37:36.340
which is Ireland's
music Association --

00:37:36.340 --> 00:37:41.810
you also have a branch of that
organization here in the area

00:37:41.810 --> 00:37:44.440
of Washington, D.C. Baltimore.

00:37:44.440 --> 00:37:47.560
And I should remind
you that [inaudible]

00:37:47.560 --> 00:37:53.430
in Bethesda is hosting its
annual Mad Week next week,

00:37:53.430 --> 00:37:55.460
which is music and dance week.

00:37:55.460 --> 00:38:00.360
And please take home some
information from outside.

00:38:00.360 --> 00:38:05.110
And if you're free, it's
a wonderful way to engage

00:38:05.110 --> 00:38:10.260
in what we call some wonderfully
constructive musical enjoyment

00:38:10.260 --> 00:38:12.510
and laziness.

00:38:12.510 --> 00:38:15.700
All constructive, of course.

00:38:15.700 --> 00:38:17.570
But back to Clare.

00:38:17.570 --> 00:38:24.680
In 1954 [speaking Irish]
came together in County Clare

00:38:24.680 --> 00:38:28.700
and they campaigned to bring
the All-Ireland Flack Hill Music

00:38:28.700 --> 00:38:30.240
Festival to the region.

00:38:30.240 --> 00:38:33.910
This is the World's
Fair of Irish music.

00:38:33.910 --> 00:38:38.150
And indeed, they made
that happen in 1956.

00:38:38.150 --> 00:38:41.920
Now, it will convene for the
fourth time in Ennis next month.

00:38:41.920 --> 00:38:45.480
So if you're in Ireland
between August 14th to 21st,

00:38:45.480 --> 00:38:48.100
you should not miss this event.

00:38:48.100 --> 00:38:51.890
Now Reid was a very
interesting gentleman.

00:38:51.890 --> 00:38:55.690
He was what I describe
as a Renaissance man,

00:38:55.690 --> 00:39:00.590
interested in classical music,
jazz, philosophy, and athletics.

00:39:00.590 --> 00:39:04.510
He came to County Clare to work
as a civil engineer in the 1930s

00:39:04.510 --> 00:39:08.850
and he broke all the rules
of social engagement.

00:39:08.850 --> 00:39:12.890
He did not stay and associate
with members of his own class.

00:39:12.890 --> 00:39:18.260
He sought out the plebs, the people
who played traditional music,

00:39:18.260 --> 00:39:22.180
sang songs, and engaged
in traditional dancing,

00:39:22.180 --> 00:39:29.670 position:56%
which was not kosher among bourgeois
society in Ireland in the 1940s.

00:39:29.670 --> 00:39:34.910
So Reid stepped away from that
bourgeois small-town world

00:39:34.910 --> 00:39:39.970
and became a cultural
revolutionary in every sense.

00:39:41.750 --> 00:39:46.810
He campaigned vigorously to bring
the All-Ireland Music Festival

00:39:46.810 --> 00:39:49.040
to the region and succeeded.

00:39:49.040 --> 00:39:53.910 position:56%
Now this new forum attracted musical
exiles from Britain and America,

00:39:53.910 --> 00:39:56.890
and it marked a turning point
when traditional musicians

00:39:56.890 --> 00:40:00.810
for the first time
claimed urban space.

00:40:00.810 --> 00:40:04.860
This kind of music was a
traditional rural form of music

00:40:04.860 --> 00:40:07.740
that you would not usually find

00:40:07.740 --> 00:40:10.880
in metropolitan Dublin
or Limerick or Cork.

00:40:10.880 --> 00:40:16.990 position:56%
And finally, with the arrival of
the music festival, the feile ceoil,

00:40:16.990 --> 00:40:22.480
people came to perform
music in urban spaces.

00:40:22.480 --> 00:40:26.540
A model of civic engagement,
tourism, and business enterprise,

00:40:26.540 --> 00:40:32.630
the 1956 festival in Ennis was also
a site of visceral public discourse

00:40:32.630 --> 00:40:35.430
on Irish musical authenticity.

00:40:35.430 --> 00:40:40.890
Not least the issue of whether
set dancing was actually Irish.

00:40:40.890 --> 00:40:42.580
Was it authentic?

00:40:42.580 --> 00:40:44.420
Most people didn't think so.

00:40:44.420 --> 00:40:48.250
In fact, people saw it
as a foreign abomination.

00:40:48.250 --> 00:40:52.620
The people who belonged to the
Gaelic League especially saw it

00:40:52.620 --> 00:41:00.030 position:56%
as something quote/unquote that came
to Ireland with Cromwell's dragoons.

00:41:00.030 --> 00:41:02.550
What an awful legacy.

00:41:02.550 --> 00:41:07.580
And, in fact, it took most of four
decades for traditional set dancing

00:41:07.580 --> 00:41:14.540
to purge itself of this
strange, European historiography.

00:41:14.540 --> 00:41:17.920
Indeed, the feile itself was
an acoustic lieu de memoire

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:23.830
of par excellence, thanks to the
great Robbie McMahon [phonetic],

00:41:23.830 --> 00:41:27.120
a ballot maker who
immortalized it in song.

00:41:27.120 --> 00:41:32.630
The feile down in Ennis in
1956 is still remembered today

00:41:32.630 --> 00:41:36.360
as a rare Nirvana of
traditional song,

00:41:36.360 --> 00:41:42.190
particularly because of
its initial excitement.

00:41:42.190 --> 00:41:45.790
This was Clare's Woodstock,
if you will.

00:41:45.790 --> 00:41:51.290
And even last year you see
here one of the two ceili bands

00:41:51.290 --> 00:41:55.670 position:56%
that traveled to Ireland from Japan.

00:41:55.670 --> 00:42:00.650
Twenty ensembles like this
competing for the world title

00:42:00.650 --> 00:42:04.170
of Irish ceili band music.

00:42:04.170 --> 00:42:05.850
A six hour marathon.

00:42:05.850 --> 00:42:08.010
Not for the weak of heart.

00:42:08.010 --> 00:42:09.710
[ Laughter ]

00:42:09.710 --> 00:42:13.190
And if you're in Ireland
again, as I say, in August,

00:42:13.190 --> 00:42:18.380
you will probably get to
hear the Toyota ceili band

00:42:18.380 --> 00:42:21.460
who won a standing
ovation from the crowd.

00:42:21.460 --> 00:42:25.030
They did not win the
title, by the way,

00:42:25.030 --> 00:42:26.930
but they certainly
changed the feile.

00:42:26.930 --> 00:42:32.460
Ireland's traditional
soundscape experienced accelerated

00:42:32.460 --> 00:42:35.560
commodification between the 1960s

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:38.710
until the Celtic Tiger
boom in the 1990s.

00:42:38.710 --> 00:42:43.630
If this new departure was linked
to tourism, regional development,

00:42:43.630 --> 00:42:45.670
and new professional opportunities,

00:42:45.670 --> 00:42:53.110
it also fueled an increasing
excitement among young people

00:42:53.110 --> 00:42:56.530
who for the first time choose
to learn traditional music

00:42:56.530 --> 00:43:00.250
in formal educational settings.

00:43:00.250 --> 00:43:04.130
Intercultural organization
of the music of Clare shifted

00:43:04.130 --> 00:43:10.640
in the 1960s away from rural
kitchens and country settings

00:43:10.640 --> 00:43:14.290
into formal school rooms.

00:43:14.290 --> 00:43:20.900 position:56%
Where we had a tradition of informal
classes, now the music became part

00:43:20.900 --> 00:43:23.300
of the school curriculum.

00:43:23.300 --> 00:43:26.650
In the same way as a
child going to school

00:43:26.650 --> 00:43:31.720
in Ireland could learn Gaelic,
they also now had the opportunity

00:43:31.720 --> 00:43:33.790
to learn traditional music.

00:43:33.790 --> 00:43:35.680
One of the key architects

00:43:35.680 --> 00:43:41.480
of this pedagogical revolution
was Frank Custy who began teaching

00:43:41.480 --> 00:43:44.990
in the small hamlet
of Tulla in 1963.

00:43:44.990 --> 00:43:48.580 position:56%
In a sense, taught music to hundreds

00:43:48.580 --> 00:43:52.580
of young people for
most of 50 years.

00:43:52.580 --> 00:43:57.250 position:56%
Many of his students, among them
Sharon Shannon and James [inaudible]

00:43:57.250 --> 00:44:02.260
and went on to become superstars
of the Celtic music industry.

00:44:02.260 --> 00:44:07.220
When the manufacturing industries
have come and gone from Clare,

00:44:07.220 --> 00:44:12.580
tourism has long been its
economic and cultural elixir.

00:44:12.580 --> 00:44:16.750
In the early 19th century,
steamboats transported day trippers

00:44:16.750 --> 00:44:22.460
from Shannon down the river to
Kilrush and Kilkee from Limerick.

00:44:22.460 --> 00:44:28.200 position:56%
While Bianconi coaches made overland
trips for those willing to put

00:44:28.200 --> 00:44:32.230
up with the discomfort of
bad roads and poor lodgings.

00:44:32.230 --> 00:44:36.020
However, the completion from
Ennis to Limerick of the Railway

00:44:36.020 --> 00:44:41.000
in 1859 brought new traffic
along the River Fergus valley.

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:45.820
And eventually, Clare's famous
railroad, the West Clare Railway --

00:44:45.820 --> 00:44:51.500
it was always late, at least
according to Percy French --

00:44:51.500 --> 00:44:56.290
in the 1880s finally opened
up access to the coast.

00:44:56.290 --> 00:45:00.840 position:56%
Victorian tourists, however, were
very different from the mass tourism

00:45:00.840 --> 00:45:04.690
that developed in Clare
after World War II.

00:45:04.690 --> 00:45:08.710
Victorian tourists were
aristocrats, professional families,

00:45:08.710 --> 00:45:12.030
who frequented the seaside
resorts in Kilkee and Spanish Point

00:45:12.030 --> 00:45:16.300
and Lahinch or indeed they
went to take the sulfur baths

00:45:16.300 --> 00:45:21.420
in Lisdoonvarna at holiday in
expensive lodges and hotels

00:45:21.420 --> 00:45:27.790
that were accessible only to
the rich and the well-endowed.

00:45:27.790 --> 00:45:30.410
In contrast, the development
of Shannon

00:45:30.410 --> 00:45:34.360
in the 1950s opens the
floodgates to cheap holidays

00:45:34.360 --> 00:45:38.740
for returning immigrants, and
particularly Irish Americans,

00:45:38.740 --> 00:45:42.580
many of whom made a
once-in-a-lifetime trip home,

00:45:42.580 --> 00:45:46.670
particularly after seeing
John Wayne and Maureen O'Hara

00:45:46.670 --> 00:45:50.370
in that famous movie in the 1950s.

00:45:50.370 --> 00:45:54.960
If mass tourism created seasonal
and full-time jobs in the transport

00:45:54.960 --> 00:45:59.640
and service industry, it
also fueled a huge surge

00:45:59.640 --> 00:46:02.330
in the heritage industry.

00:46:02.330 --> 00:46:06.210
So we began packaging
tradition and artifacts

00:46:06.210 --> 00:46:09.320
from medieval castles
to folk villages.

00:46:09.320 --> 00:46:12.440
And indeed, the people
who packaged Clare

00:46:12.440 --> 00:46:15.860
for tourist consumption
walked a very fine line

00:46:15.860 --> 00:46:19.780
between preserving the past
and embracing the future.

00:46:19.780 --> 00:46:24.490
Yes, they capitalized on movie
and postcard images of Ireland

00:46:24.490 --> 00:46:27.900
and they capitalized on
the marketing synergies

00:46:27.900 --> 00:46:30.460
of airline and vacation companies.

00:46:30.460 --> 00:46:33.520
And indeed by the 1970s
Clare tourism kicked

00:46:33.520 --> 00:46:38.690
into high gear offering medieval
banquets, music festivals,

00:46:38.690 --> 00:46:42.810
golfing holidays, river
cruises and luxury tours

00:46:42.810 --> 00:46:46.690 position:56%
through Clare's unspoiled heartland.

00:46:46.690 --> 00:46:52.030
Positioning itself as a homely and
a pastoral antidote to the speed

00:46:52.030 --> 00:46:55.780
and the stress of the 21st
century, Clare continues

00:46:55.780 --> 00:47:00.840
to market its history, its cultural
capital and its exotic landscape.

00:47:00.840 --> 00:47:04.240
Ironically, the products
and the vistas

00:47:04.240 --> 00:47:08.420
that are packaged today are
largely the same as those

00:47:08.420 --> 00:47:12.690
that first enticed Victorian
tourists to the region a century

00:47:12.690 --> 00:47:16.420
and a half ago: the
Crescent Strand in Kilkee,

00:47:16.420 --> 00:47:19.940
the Spa Wells in Lisdoonvarna,
the archaeological wonders

00:47:19.940 --> 00:47:24.520
of the Byrne -- which you've seen
-- and of course Clare's icon,

00:47:24.520 --> 00:47:26.550
the Cliffs of Moher, the latter

00:47:26.550 --> 00:47:30.930
of which attracted a million
visitors a year during the height

00:47:30.930 --> 00:47:35.170
of the Celtic Tiger boom.

00:47:35.170 --> 00:47:38.740
Now not all cultural heritage
however fared as well as that

00:47:38.740 --> 00:47:40.720
which was packaged for tourists.

00:47:40.720 --> 00:47:44.190
Juxtapositioned with the
rise of industrial tourism

00:47:44.190 --> 00:47:47.310
in Clare was an equally
precipitous decline

00:47:47.310 --> 00:47:49.880 position:56%
in the Irish language in the region.

00:47:49.880 --> 00:47:54.770
In the early 19th century, most
of Clare was Irish-speaking.

00:47:54.770 --> 00:47:58.540
Throughout the 18th century,
English was confined mainly

00:47:58.540 --> 00:48:03.010
to colonial bureaucrats, the
courts, and the Protestant church.

00:48:03.010 --> 00:48:06.050
It made progress outside of
the rural areas by the end

00:48:06.050 --> 00:48:09.600
of the century as a result
of newspapers, commerce,

00:48:09.600 --> 00:48:13.960
and indeed British soldiers
billeted in garrison towns.

00:48:13.960 --> 00:48:18.370
The primary conduit of English in
19th century Clare and other parts

00:48:18.370 --> 00:48:22.250
of Ireland were what we call the
national schools that were set

00:48:22.250 --> 00:48:25.620
up throughout Ireland
thanks to Lord Stanley

00:48:25.620 --> 00:48:29.700
who passed an educational
bill in the 1830s.

00:48:29.700 --> 00:48:32.610
That's the same Lord
Stanley who many

00:48:32.610 --> 00:48:34.200
of you hockey fans
appreciate so much.

00:48:34.200 --> 00:48:36.390
[ Laughter ]

00:48:36.390 --> 00:48:42.290 position:56%
Designed to educate
quote/unquote good English children.

00:48:42.290 --> 00:48:43.700
I'll say that again.

00:48:43.700 --> 00:48:47.610
Designed to educate
good English children,

00:48:47.610 --> 00:48:49.900
these national schools
became bedrocks

00:48:49.900 --> 00:48:53.440 position:56%
of education in most Irish villages.

00:48:53.440 --> 00:48:57.050
They discouraged the use
of Irish in the classroom

00:48:57.050 --> 00:49:02.510
and they had a tally stick which
child wore around his or her neck.

00:49:02.510 --> 00:49:07.440
And the tally stick was designed
so that your parents were required

00:49:07.440 --> 00:49:12.110
to put a little notch on the stick
every time you spoke Irish at home.

00:49:12.110 --> 00:49:15.930 position:56%
And when you showed up at school the
following day, you were punished.

00:49:15.930 --> 00:49:20.570
Now this story was told
to me by this gentleman

00:49:20.570 --> 00:49:23.160
when I was about my son's age.

00:49:23.160 --> 00:49:25.200
And his name was Anraoi de Blaca.

00:49:25.200 --> 00:49:28.390
He was one of the last of
the Gaelic speakers of Clare.

00:49:28.390 --> 00:49:37.500 position:56%
And tragically, in my lifetime, I've
lived through the actual decline

00:49:37.500 --> 00:49:40.250
of the Gaelic language,
the oldest spoken language

00:49:40.250 --> 00:49:43.190
in Western Europe, in
my particular region.

00:49:43.190 --> 00:49:45.920
However, north and south of Clare,

00:49:45.920 --> 00:49:50.550
Irish is still very much
a successful vernacular

00:49:50.550 --> 00:49:56.560
and very much part of the
Irish cultural mainframe.

00:49:56.560 --> 00:50:02.330
Clare's recent Irish-speaking past,
while inaccessible and invisible

00:50:02.330 --> 00:50:06.720
to most tourists and non-natives,
had a very profound impact

00:50:06.720 --> 00:50:09.140
on its music and folk life.

00:50:09.140 --> 00:50:13.790
Clare musicians, people like Willie
Clancy, Chris Droni [phonetic],

00:50:13.790 --> 00:50:17.940
were all first-generation
English language speakers.

00:50:17.940 --> 00:50:24.190 position:56%
They grew up in a bicultural world
shaped by a Gaelic past that endured

00:50:24.190 --> 00:50:27.850
for centuries on modern
times that emerged

00:50:27.850 --> 00:50:31.230
from the colonial ashes
of World War I.

00:50:31.230 --> 00:50:36.280
Their speech, syntax, and their
wits reflected an older world

00:50:36.280 --> 00:50:39.210
of poets and characters.

00:50:39.210 --> 00:50:44.950
And their collective psyche really
sat uncomfortably beside the

00:50:44.950 --> 00:50:48.980
progressive crust of
the 20th century.

00:50:48.980 --> 00:50:54.240
Now new media and new
audiences reshaped Clare music

00:50:54.240 --> 00:50:57.090
since Ireland joined the
European Economic Community,

00:50:57.090 --> 00:51:01.310
which you know today
as the EU, in 1973.

00:51:01.310 --> 00:51:05.820
Less preoccupied with jaded
notions of authenticity,

00:51:05.820 --> 00:51:11.420
young audiences reshuffled older
definitions of Irish music,

00:51:11.420 --> 00:51:15.610
moving it away in a sense from
its former ethnic moorings

00:51:15.610 --> 00:51:17.960
into mainstream culture.

00:51:17.960 --> 00:51:21.600
Countercultural and transcultural
elements were also scooped

00:51:21.600 --> 00:51:27.950
up in this trajectory, particularly
in the village of Doolin,

00:51:27.950 --> 00:51:31.210
which I'm sure many of you know.

00:51:31.210 --> 00:51:33.720
In Clare, the village of
Doolin and the small town

00:51:33.720 --> 00:51:37.580
of Milltown Mel Bay became nodal
points in this transformation.

00:51:37.580 --> 00:51:43.740
Now 40 years later, Doolin is a
paradoxical musical sanctuary.

00:51:43.740 --> 00:51:48.900
In a sense, it's a postmodern
simulacrum of its former self

00:51:48.900 --> 00:51:52.400
where today the people who came

00:51:52.400 --> 00:51:58.790
and settled I Doolin
radically outnumber the natives

00:51:58.790 --> 00:52:00.180
of the village.

00:52:00.180 --> 00:52:08.110
So the pilgrims now outnumber those
they came to worship and honor.

00:52:08.110 --> 00:52:12.940
What's interesting is that Doolin
has become highly commodified,

00:52:12.940 --> 00:52:17.200
as you can see, with the
confusion at the crossroads.

00:52:17.200 --> 00:52:20.380
Whereas Milltown Mel Bay, on the
other hand, which is the site

00:52:20.380 --> 00:52:23.880
of Ireland's largest summer
school has avoided the paradox

00:52:23.880 --> 00:52:25.950
of its northern neighbors.

00:52:25.950 --> 00:52:31.420
Now we're running a little short of
