00:53:36.860 --> 00:53:41.130
They are more Irish than the
Irish themselves in many respects.

00:53:41.130 --> 00:53:45.590
We speak about the Normans who
came to Ireland in the 13th

00:53:45.590 --> 00:53:50.590
and 14th centuries becoming more
Irish than the Irish themselves.

00:53:50.590 --> 00:53:51.980
They stopped speaking French.

00:53:51.980 --> 00:53:54.180
I love saying this in
Québec to my students.

00:53:54.180 --> 00:53:56.350
[ Laughter ]

00:53:56.350 --> 00:54:00.540
They stopped speaking French
so that they can know, learn,

00:54:00.540 --> 00:54:04.180
and speak Irish and
become Gaelic poets.

00:54:04.180 --> 00:54:05.480
And this is the kind

00:54:05.480 --> 00:54:09.650
of transformation we've had
throughout late medieval Ireland.

00:54:09.650 --> 00:54:12.960
And I think it's intriguing
that what's happening today

00:54:12.960 --> 00:54:17.700
in the Irish world soundscape
is that throughout the world,

00:54:17.700 --> 00:54:21.900
not just in the United States
or Canada, but in South America,

00:54:21.900 --> 00:54:27.220
Southeast Asia, Eastern Europe,
Alaska, places along the edges

00:54:27.220 --> 00:54:30.660
of Western civilization -- if
I can use that expression --

00:54:30.660 --> 00:54:36.670
are now becoming inducted and
becoming excited about Irish music

00:54:36.670 --> 00:54:41.780
and dance; and in fact becoming
master performers of that genre,

00:54:41.780 --> 00:54:45.590
which is truly intriguing and very,

00:54:45.590 --> 00:54:50.080
very complementary
to Irish performers.

00:54:51.210 --> 00:54:55.870
The economic boom during the
Celtic Tiger years from 1995

00:54:55.870 --> 00:55:00.710
until 2005 also transformed
Clare's soundscape.

00:55:00.710 --> 00:55:03.940
And indeed, music became a
key element in the branding

00:55:03.940 --> 00:55:06.710
and the commodification
of the region,

00:55:06.710 --> 00:55:10.330
particularly by tourism
managers, bar owners,

00:55:10.330 --> 00:55:13.070
and other culture entrepreneurs.

00:55:13.070 --> 00:55:16.960
That a term we've become
very used to in our Ireland,

00:55:16.960 --> 00:55:19.580
cultural entrepreneurship.

00:55:19.580 --> 00:55:24.620
And music is a key
asset in that process.

00:55:24.620 --> 00:55:28.610
A time of new trends,
creative alliances,

00:55:28.610 --> 00:55:30.940
and conspicuous consumption.

00:55:30.940 --> 00:55:35.780
Cultural production in the Celtic
Tiger years spawned a whole new

00:55:35.780 --> 00:55:40.170
generation of Clare superstars
and Clare super groups.

00:55:40.170 --> 00:55:44.380
People like Sharon Shannon,
Martin Hayes, and Maura O'Connell,

00:55:44.380 --> 00:55:48.440
and indeed the Kilfenora ceili
band, who I like to describe

00:55:48.440 --> 00:55:52.920
as the avant-garde ceili
band of Celtic Tiger Ireland.

00:55:52.920 --> 00:55:56.950
They graduated from the village
hall to the national concert hall

00:55:56.950 --> 00:56:00.240
and indeed the International
Folk Festival.

00:56:00.240 --> 00:56:03.310
The [speaking Irish], the
Irish Music Association,

00:56:03.310 --> 00:56:08.250
was also synergized during
these opportunistic times,

00:56:08.250 --> 00:56:11.100
sometimes challenging
the onslaught of change

00:56:11.100 --> 00:56:16.770
and indeed more times quite
powerless to alter its trajectory.

00:56:16.770 --> 00:56:22.410
Internet sociology and indeed new
cultural flows also reconfigured

00:56:22.410 --> 00:56:25.970
Clare music particularly
outside of Clare.

00:56:25.970 --> 00:56:30.710
In the process, another
musical Clare emerged,

00:56:30.710 --> 00:56:33.910
one that was virtual on vicarious.

00:56:33.910 --> 00:56:37.970
If cultured tourism filled
the region with European

00:56:37.970 --> 00:56:42.680
and American music tourists
in the 1970s and 1980s,

00:56:42.680 --> 00:56:48.620
by the end of the century it was
not uncommon to meet young Asian,

00:56:48.620 --> 00:56:52.340
particularly Japanese and Chinese
musicians, as well as Australians

00:56:52.340 --> 00:56:58.690
and South Americans, all performing
music from Clare in Clare,

00:56:58.690 --> 00:57:01.960
and bringing that music home
to their respective nations

00:57:01.960 --> 00:57:08.350 position:56%
and spreading the music quite
passionately among their own people.

00:57:08.350 --> 00:57:11.840
As I said, they were passionate
about the region and its music.

00:57:11.840 --> 00:57:17.650
These tourist performers,
vicarious Clare people of sorts,

00:57:17.650 --> 00:57:22.120
galvanized their new identities
in sessions and in summer camps --

00:57:22.120 --> 00:57:24.400
like Mad Week, which
is happening next week.

00:57:24.400 --> 00:57:29.840
Please, if you're at all
interested come and enjoy.

00:57:29.840 --> 00:57:33.830
Now indeed there are dedicated
communities of Clare musicians

00:57:33.830 --> 00:57:41.330
in Paris, Buenos Aires, New York,
Tokyo, Washington, D.C. And indeed,

00:57:41.330 --> 00:57:45.650
few have any ethnic connection
to the region, yet they continue

00:57:45.650 --> 00:57:50.490
to redefine its soundscape
in absentia.

00:57:50.490 --> 00:57:55.340
While global culture flows
continue to create new topographies

00:57:55.340 --> 00:58:00.580
and new memories of Clare music,
they also mask deep crevices

00:58:00.580 --> 00:58:03.070
of musical forgetting and amnesia.

00:58:03.070 --> 00:58:08.270
And this, we're rather
reluctant to talk about in Clare,

00:58:08.270 --> 00:58:10.900
not least the cultural
fallout from the loss

00:58:10.900 --> 00:58:13.390 position:56%
of the Irish language in the region.

00:58:13.390 --> 00:58:18.200
While the region today basks in the
success and notoriety of its music,

00:58:18.200 --> 00:58:22.540
it seldom takes stock of the
musical losses of the past,

00:58:22.540 --> 00:58:27.220
not least the vast storehouse
of songs that disappeared

00:58:27.220 --> 00:58:32.520 position:56%
with the decline of the Irish
language, that once kept them alive.

00:58:32.520 --> 00:58:37.280
While cultural nationalists still
regard Irish traditional music is a

00:58:37.280 --> 00:58:45.520
sacred cow, a kind of lost Eden,
it is also an evolving ideoscape

00:58:45.520 --> 00:58:51.210 position:56%
where tensions between past and
present, remembering and forgetting,

00:58:51.210 --> 00:58:57.370
nationalism and revisionism collide
and rebound through various spheres

00:58:57.370 --> 00:58:59.970
of Irish cultural discourse.

00:58:59.970 --> 00:59:04.370
In this sense, players' traditional
soundscape is no different

00:59:04.370 --> 00:59:10.260
from any other soundscapes where
musicians are asked to preserve

00:59:10.260 --> 00:59:12.870
as well as perform tradition while

00:59:12.870 --> 00:59:17.150
at the same time carrying
it forward in time.

00:59:17.150 --> 00:59:23.370 position:56%
As mediators of tradition, musicians
are called upon to shape the destiny

00:59:23.370 --> 00:59:25.740
of their heritage in the world

00:59:25.740 --> 00:59:29.940
that is constantly
shifting beneath their feet.

00:59:29.940 --> 00:59:35.400
I have little doubt that this
creative and symbiotic tension

00:59:35.400 --> 00:59:39.990
between musical roots and
musical routes will continue

00:59:39.990 --> 00:59:44.470
to impact the soundscape
of Clare as it will

00:59:44.470 --> 00:59:49.360
in other traditional soundscapes
irrespective of where they are

00:59:49.360 --> 00:59:51.790
in our ever-changing world.

00:59:51.790 --> 00:59:53.590
Thank you.

